"In traditional French haute cuisine, where meals may be made up of half a dozen courses, all interspersed with entremets, the entrée was the first of the MAIN courses. It might be preceded by soup, salad or fish dishes, and was typically a relatively light course like a quiche or a soufflé, intended as a prelude to the more substantial meat, game and poultry courses that would follow. As habits surrounding fine dining became simpler, the number of courses dropped to usually three (starter, main and dessert) and the meaning of the word entrée shifted. In France, as well as the UK and other English speaking countries, it means the first course, but in much of the U.S. it means the main course."

